llm_answer:
The photoelectric equation is  

\[
E_{\text{photon}}=h\nu=\frac{hc}{\lambda}= \phi + K_{\max}
\]

where  
\(\phi\) is the work function and \(K_{\max}\) is the maximum kinetic energy of the ejected electron.

---

### 1.  Photon energy for the given wavelength  

Using \(hc\approx 1240\;\text{eV}\,\text{nm}\),

\[
E_{\text{photon}}=\frac{1240\;\text{eV}\,\text{nm}}{305\;\text{nm}}
           = 4.0656\;\text{eV}
\]

---

### 2.  Work function of the metal  

\[
\phi = E_{\text{photon}}-K_{\max}
      = 4.0656\;\text{eV}-1.77\;\text{eV}
      = 2.2956\;\text{eV}
\]

---

### 3.  Maximum wavelength that can eject an electron  

A photon of wavelength \(\lambda_{\max}\) has just enough energy to overcome the work function, so its energy equals \(\phi\):

\[
\phi = \frac{hc}{\lambda_{\max}}
      \;\;\Longrightarrow\;\;
\lambda_{\max}= \frac{hc}{\phi}
               =\frac{1240\;\text{eV}\,\text{nm}}{2.2956\;\text{eV}}
               = 5.406\times10^{2}\;\text{nm}
\]

\[
\boxed{540.6}\;\text{nm}
\]

