The two methyl‑glycoside species arise from two different types of glucose residues.  
The 2,3‑dimethyl‑glucose comes from the “ordinary’’ (linear) residues, whereas the
1,2,3,6‑tetramethyl‑glucose is produced exclusively from the residues that are
branch points.  
Hence the fraction of branch‑point residues equals the ratio of the moles of
1,2,3,6‑tetramethyl‑glucose to the total moles of all residues:

\[
\text{fraction}_{\text{branch}}=\frac{n_{\text{1,2,3,6‑tetra}}}
       {n_{\text{2,3‑di}}+n_{\text{1,2,3,6‑tetra}}}
      =\frac{0.4\times10^{-6}\;\text{mol}}
             {(50+0.4)\times10^{-6}\;\text{mol}}
      =\frac{0.4}{50.4}\approx 7.9\times10^{-3}\;.
\]

\[
\boxed{7.9\times10^{-3}}
\]

