llm_answer:
The combustion of an alkane is

\[
\ce{C8H18 + 9 O2 -> 8 CO2 + 9 H2O}
\]

Using the average bond enthalpies to compute \(\Delta H_{\text{comb}}\):

**Bonds broken**

\[
\begin{aligned}
&\text{C–C bonds: }7 \times 347 = 2429 \text{ kJ/mol} \\
&\text{C–H bonds: }18 \times 413 = 7434 \text{ kJ/mol} \\
&\text{O=O bonds: }9 \times 498 = 4482 \text{ kJ/mol}
\end{aligned}
\]

\[
\text{Total broken} = 2429 + 7434 + 4482 = 14345 \text{ kJ/mol}
\]

**Bonds formed**

\[
\begin{aligned}
&\text{C=O bonds in } \ce{CO2}: 8 \times 2 \times 805 = 12880 \text{ kJ/mol} \\
&\text{O–H bonds in } \ce{H2O}: 9 \times 2 \times 464 = 8352 \text{ kJ/mol}
\end{aligned}
\]

\[
\text{Total formed} = 12880 + 8352 = 21232 \text{ kJ/mol}
\]

**Enthalpy of combustion**

\[
\Delta H_{\text{comb}} = \sum E_{\text{broken}} - \sum E_{\text{formed}}
  = 14345 - 21232 = -6887 \text{ kJ mol}^{-1}
\]

\[
\boxed{-6887}\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}
\]

