The heat released per second \( \dot Q \) is  

\[
\dot Q\;\propto\;\frac{\Delta H^\circ}{\sqrt{M}}
\]

for a fuel of relative molecular mass \(M\).  
With the same pressure the ratio of heat rates for hydrogen (\(M_{\mathrm H_2}=2\)) and methane (\(M_{\mathrm{CH_4}}=16\)) is

\[
\frac{\dot Q_{\mathrm H_2}}{\dot Q_{\mathrm{CH_4}}}
=\frac{\displaystyle\frac{\lvert\Delta H^\circ_{\mathrm H_2}\rvert}{\sqrt{2}}}
{\displaystyle\frac{\lvert\Delta H^\circ_{\mathrm{CH_4}}\rvert}{\sqrt{16}}}
= \frac{285.8\,\text{kJ mol}^{-1}\;\times 4}
{890.3\,\text{kJ mol}^{-1}\;\times 1.414}
\approx 0.908 .
\]

Thus, the burner fueled by hydrogen releases about \(0.91\) times as much heat per second as the burner fueled by methane.  

\[
\boxed{0.91}
\]

