llm_answer:
The laminar flame speed gives the velocity of the unburned mixture relative to the flame front.  
Hence the volumetric flow rate through the burner tube is

\[
\dot V_{\text{mix}} = S_L\,A
\]

where  
\(S_L = 0.38\;\text{m s}^{-1}\) and   
\(A = \dfrac{\pi d^{2}}{4}\) with \(d = 8\;\text{mm}=8\times10^{-3}\;\text{m}\).

\[
A = \frac{\pi(8\times10^{-3})^{2}}{4}
   = 5.03\times10^{-5}\;\text{m}^{2}
\]

\[
\dot V_{\text{mix}} = 0.38 \times 5.03\times10^{-5}
                    = 1.91\times10^{-5}\;\text{m}^{3}\text{s}^{-1}
                    = 1.91\times10^{-2}\;\text{L\,s}^{-1}
                    = 1.15\;\text{L\,min}^{-1}
\]

For an equivalence ratio \(\lambda = 1.2\),

\[
\frac{\text{air moles}}{\text{total moles}}
 = \frac{1/\lambda}{1+1/\lambda}
 = \frac{1/1.2}{1+1/1.2}
 = 0.889
\]

Thus the air volumetric flow rate is

\[
\dot V_{\text{air}} = 0.889\,\dot V_{\text{mix}}
                    = 0.889 \times 1.15
                    \approx 1.02\;\text{L\,min}^{-1}
\]

\[
\boxed{1.02}\;\text{L/min}
\]

